prefer-object-params

Warn on reusable function definitions with 3 or more positional parameters and
prefer a single object parameter.

Source: custom rule for lintcn
Severity: warn (does not block CI)

The goal is to stop agents from growing reusable APIs through long positional
parameter lists. Once a helper needs three or more inputs, a single object
parameter is usually easier to read, easier to evolve, and harder to call in the
wrong order.

The Problem

These definitions make call sites harder to scan and easier to mix up:

  function createUser(name: string, email: string, role: string) {
    return { name, email, role }
  }

  class UserService {
    update(name: string, email: string, role: string) {
      return { name, email, role }
    }
  }

  const handlers = {
    update: (name: string, email: string, role: string) => {
      return { name, email, role }
    },
  }

What Gets Flagged

- Function declarations with 3 or more positional parameters
- Named function expressions and arrow functions assigned to variables or
  properties
- Class methods, constructors, and methods on named object literals

What Is Allowed

- Definitions with 0, 1, or 2 positional parameters
- Functions that already use a single object parameter
- Inline callbacks and lambdas passed directly at the use site
- Inline object literal handlers passed directly into another call
- `this` parameters do not count toward the positional total

Examples

Flagged:

  function createUser(name: string, email: string, role: string) {
    return { name, email, role }
  }

  const createUser = (name: string, email: string, role: string) => {
    return { name, email, role }
  }

Allowed:

  function createUser(options: {
    name: string
    email: string
    role: string
  }) {
    return options
  }

  items.map((value, index, array) => value + index + array.length)
